                <p class="text-justify">Tourists can go swimming, boating, fishing, canoeing, and kayaking, or head to Rock Park on the Truckee River for white water rafting. This city also offers to learn about the region's mining, ranching, and railroading history by touring the Sparks Museum and Cultural Center or attending one of the many annual events the city hosts. </p>

                <h4 class="text-justify">10. Las Vegas</h4>
                <p class="text-justify">Last but not least is the city of Las Vegas. It is the largest city in all of Nevada, just before Reno. Las Vegas is famous for its pompous styles, cloaked with sky-kissing buildings and penthouses. It is also the core of many industrial centers. </p>
